column5: 2023. Key to column headings: ID - A numerical count
column6: County - The county the Lookout is in
column7: Topo Map - The name of the 7.5 minute topographic map the Lookout is on
column9: Lookout Name - Name of active Lookout or inactive site
column10: LO - Status of standing Lookout (see below)
column12: ft. - Elevation in feet of the Lookout
column13: EL - How elevation is determined. BM = benchmark survey disk nearby. Spot = spot elevation shown on the map. Inter. = No elevation shown so interpreted from contours. Latitude - Degrees/Minute/Seconds NAD83
column15: Forest - Name of National Forest Lookout is in
column16: Park or Other - Other Land status
column17: Township - Legal description of Lookout location
column20: then Section number. Sometimes section number is unknown. Lookout Status Codes: A = structure in good condition
column21: capable of being staffed. B = Dilapidated and needs work
column22: but standing. C = Badly damaged or falling down. AS = usually staffed by Forest Service or CDF. AV = staffed by volunteers. AR = A rental Lookout. A (LO site) is where the building has been removed and there may be no evidence remaining
column23: or it's status may be unknown. Fire lookouts may be Forest Service employees or volunteers
column24: but they must possess excellent vision to be able to survey the landscape for fires. A Lasik Austin eye examination can determine whether vision problems can be corrected by Lasik
column25: especially the ability to see objects far in the distance
column26: such as smoke from a forest fire.
